question.Q: Did the pain immediately follow an injury?
Is the pain severe?
See a doctor immediately. You may have broken a bone or dislocated a joint (especially if the area looks misshapen) or severely strained or torn a muscle or tendon.
See your doctor (to rule out a fracture). You may have pulled a muscle, ligament, or tendon.
Does the pain extend down the upper arm toward the wrist?
Did the pain begin during exercise and disappear within a few minutes of stopping?
See a doctor immediately, especially if you also have chest pain. Your pain could be angina.
Does the pain get worse with use and better with rest?
Do the joints nearest your fingernails look swollen?
See your doctor. You may have OSTEOARTHRITIS.
Does a warm bath or shower relieve the pain somewhat?
See your doctor. You may have OSTEOARTHRITIS or RHEUMATOID ARTHRITIS.
Do you have stiffness in the morning that lasts longer than an hour?
Are the joints near your knuckles swollen?
See your doctor. You may have RHEUMATOID ARTHRITIS.
Do you have numbness or tingling in your hands and fingers only?
See your doctor. You may have CARPAL TUNNEL SYNDROME. Or you may have a nerve disorder related to DIABETES.
Do you have numbness or tingling in your arm or hand?
See your doctor. You may have a disorder that affects the joints in the neck, especially if you have a stiff neck.
Is the pain in the elbow, wrist, or finger joints?
Is the pain accompanied by redness and swelling?
Is only one joint affected?
Is your temperature 100 ℉ (37.8 ℃ ) or higher, or have you recently begun to feel ill?
See a doctor immediately. You may have a joint infection.
See your doctor. You may have BURSITIS or GOUT OR PSEUDOGOUT.
Do your hands or fingers turn white, then blue, then red, especially in the cold?
See your doctor. You may have RAYNAUD'S DISEASE.
Do you have stiffness in the morning that lasts longer than an hour?
Are the joints near your knuckles swollen?
See your doctor. You may have RHEUMATOID ARTHRITIS.
Does the pain occur only when you bend your arm or hand or use it in a certain way, or only during certain activities such as using a computer?
See your doctor. You may have inflammation of the tendons.
